  "relevant_summary": "- UK: Multiple studies found reducing or stopping grazing increased shrub abundance or cover; common heather increased under lower livestock density; some studies reported mixed effects. Fencing to exclude livestock increased shrub cover/abundance and heather biomass/height; however, in peat bogs shrub cover often did not change overall, though heather increased in drier areas. Management with reduced grazing increased heath vegetation and heather cover. [1607, 1545, 1734, 647]\n- South Africa: Reducing or stopping grazing increased shrub abundance or cover. [1607]\n- Netherlands: Ungrazed sites had higher dwarf shrub cover. [1607]\n- Spain: Reducing grazing increased cover of western gorse. [1607]\n- USA: Stopping grazing did not increase shrub abundance in two trials; in shrublands, fencing led to decreased woody plant cover in one study and mixed/no change in others; in peatland fens, excluding/removing livestock increased shrub cover in one study. [1607, 1545, 1734]\n- France: Ungrazed sites had higher cover of ericaceous shrubs but lower cover of non\u2011ericaceous shrubs than grazed sites. [1607]\n- Germany and Denmark: Excluding livestock (fencing) increased shrub biomass or heather presence/cover. [1545]\n- Australia: In bogs, excluding livestock typically had no effect on shrub cover. [1734]\n- Chile: Excluding or removing livestock increased shrub cover in a peatland. [1734]",
